</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="21DF9E02805B0E7FE41CD7107B84F154" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" type="type">
<paragraph id="E043A691269F77245F4F2670B3DA8A94" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Type.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A29091F25D1CD6DFF6044AC6ED1ACAC4" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
SOUTH AFRICA, Free State, 
<emphasis id="F300F3A7A8760B346E68CE8958467CAA" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Boedecker</emphasis>
s.n. (lectotype GOET-002454, designated by 
<bibRefCitation id="8E9064D485DF7B715E1820B53BE671D6" author="Meeuse, ADL" journalOrPublisher="Flora of Southern Africa" pageId="207" pageNumber="208" pagination="1 - 138" refId="B226" refString="Meeuse, ADL, Welman, WG, 2000. Convolvulaceae. Flora of Southern Africa volume 28 (part 1): 1 - 138" title="Convolvulaceae." volume="volume 28" year="2000">Meeuse and Welman 2000</bibRefCitation>
: 40).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6748B6CD99C1389CFE6F925495B0E732" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" type="description">
<paragraph id="AE3B5A76B66A574706C3C9C7C055601D" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F3C78F141B8F01D8D02A9CE5884D863C" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
Perennial herb with woody taproot from which spread numerous stems to 60 cm, plant covered in adpressed brown to silvery hairs. Leaves 1-2.5 
<normalizedToken id="CE312EF87EF4DFEA557E61BDC32882FB" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.5-2 cm, lanceolate to ovate in outline, variable in form from pinnatisect to palmately 5-lobed, often with the terminal lobe much longer and deeply toothed and the basal lobes bifid, base truncate to shallowly cordate; petioles 1-5 mm long. Flowers solitary, axillary, pedicellate but not pedunculate (rarely peduncle to 1mm); bracteoles 1-2 mm long, subulate; pedicels 2-6(-10) mm, outer sepals 4-5(-6) 
<normalizedToken id="99370684CC5C0DF44A1B53DA176A2FC5" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2-3 mm, ovate to oblong-elliptic, acute; corolla 7-10 mm long, pink or white, shallowly lobed, midpetaline bands pubescent with brown hairs; ovary glabrous; style glabrous, divided 2.5 mm above base; stigmas 2.5 mm, slightly widened upwards. Capsule glabrous; seeds glabrous, smooth but muricate on angles. [
<bibRefCitation id="08B6F243E5943B2726997E71D4D6698A" author="Meeuse, ADL" journalOrPublisher="Bothalia" pageId="207" pageNumber="208" pagination="641 - 792" refId="B225" refString="Meeuse, ADL, 1958 1957. The South African Convolvulaceae. Bothalia 6: 641 - 792" title="The South African Convolvulaceae." volume="6" year="1958">Meeuse 1958</bibRefCitation>
: 674; 
<bibRefCitation id="2F3FBA2FC1ECAA8D13710E7ECC71B155" author="Meeuse, ADL" journalOrPublisher="Flora of Southern Africa" pageId="207" pageNumber="208" pagination="1 - 138" refId="B226" refString="Meeuse, ADL, Welman, WG, 2000. Convolvulaceae. Flora of Southern Africa volume 28 (part 1): 1 - 138" title="Convolvulaceae." volume="volume 28" year="2000">Meeuse and Welman 2000</bibRefCitation>
: 40 (map)]
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="570F3A41A40713B19DC2E8B92692EC2D" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="93CD51E964954DC1F4DF7EB52E5831F3" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B9DB0C34EB23A6DCBA1EA7B6D47BB88E" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
South Africa except KwaZulu-Natal (
<emphasis id="11260647C04DA1DB26B7928E10C6D0F6" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Prosser</emphasis>
1529, 
<emphasis id="5A5F2A03AD09E5C29B3CF189BDC8FF97" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Werger</emphasis>
289, 
<emphasis id="F6E4E95F59D6077EBE188B880B97883F" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Shaw</emphasis>
123, 
<emphasis id="E0376E44B6C28FC5AF05D8BAA0D1D316" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Brierley</emphasis>
173, 
<emphasis id="3FCE21E753934035FD70F49B832D855A" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Flanagan</emphasis>
2112, 
<emphasis id="E4878607B59324060037FA1EEB5205D1" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Duparquet</emphasis>
107).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8729997526C469F4E537D23539C16A3B" lastPageId="72" lastPageNumber="73" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" type="notes">
<paragraph id="CBA7E8D070715E2D4F9D981F5D0C782C" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="310DFB6F71731C6CA3E9FA1C1B9D7911" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
Distinguished by the solitary, pedicellate flowers and near absence of peduncles combined with the very small calyx, the sepals usually about 5 mm long and thinly covered in brownish hairs. The inflorescence is similar to that of 
<taxonomicName id="8EB999BA49F8C5373E48784CC735982A" authorityName="Hook., Bot. Mag. 70: t. 4065. 1844. (Hooker" authorityYear="1844" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus ocellatus" order="Solanales" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ocellatus">
<emphasis id="AE5D03C28697BB8C31126882DDD31E63" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Convolvulus ocellatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but in that species the calyx is&gt;6 mm long and the whole plant is densely tomentose. It can be confused with 
<taxonomicName id="92629F1CBC31E668CBCED6790C1D7CEC" authorityName="Thunb., Prodr. Pl. Cap. 35. 1794. (Thunberg" authorityYear="1794" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus multifidus" order="Solanales" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="multifidus">
<emphasis id="BBA534575E931E7EE918D408281B1B1D" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Convolvulus multifidus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but in 
<taxonomicName id="ED5212ADC05C748C239711F1388F3E7D" authorityName="Thunb., Prodr. Pl. Cap. 35. 1794. (Thunberg" authorityYear="1794" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus multifidus" order="Solanales" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="multifidus">
<emphasis id="3A7E14260B5C87BE5F14C37C75022351" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Convolvulus multifidus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the calyx is larger. It could also be confused with 
<taxonomicName id="2DD0756CDC90C265A490B2DC9BB0936B" authorityName="J. R. I. Wood &amp; R. W. Scotland" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus austroafricanus" order="Solanales" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="austroafricanus">
<emphasis id="03DA27540CD7137D1AE1C849D4517C10" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Convolvulus austroafricanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but that species usually has several flowers which are always borne on a peduncle.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3CECA35240C02CD6FBFC76A520A1F562" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">
<pageBreakToken id="B2E771147C13954FFD93B7BE23D6DD54" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" start="start">There</pageBreakToken>
are specimens apparently intermediate with 
<taxonomicName id="56BE656579100631379B79DC55818812" authorityName="J. R. I. Wood &amp; R. W. Scotland" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus austroafricanus" order="Solanales" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="austroafricanus">
<emphasis id="BF1057C7BA8EF35F65D0827A8DF42CEF" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Convolvulus austroafricanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
including 
<emphasis id="AC481A5F1C0EB84392CFC103B3117680" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Moss</emphasis>
4718 from Belmont, 
<emphasis id="EE0BEB42F1905CE41DD142DD594A2E78" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Goosseno</emphasis>
728 from Free State and 
<emphasis id="BFF67657518823F1E0AA0ACEF3005311" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Eyres</emphasis>
1820 and 
<emphasis id="941BC567D71178DCE2BA16C60847AFAA" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Jacobsen</emphasis>
1772 from Zimbabwe. These have short but very distinct peduncles 5-10 mm long which bear 1-2 flowers, similar in dimensions to 
<taxonomicName id="2BDB414131DD989E4611DACCBF18221C" authorityName="Peter, Nat. Pflanzenfam. [Engler &amp; Prantl] 4 (3 a): 36. 1891. (Peter" authorityYear="1891" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus boedeckerianus" order="Solanales" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="boedeckerianus">
<emphasis id="0C99468911BA318662010617B6AA81DC" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Convolvulus boedeckerianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Unlike 
<taxonomicName id="E1394C8CB61D7DF561217B05A5678EFC" authorityName="J. R. I. Wood &amp; R. W. Scotland" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus austroafricanus" order="Solanales" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="austroafricanus">
<emphasis id="C6F2C81C6F42B7C35FC88FA99F766EC7" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Convolvulus austroafricanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
these plants are not very hirsute. Given the increasing evidence for hybridisation within 
<taxonomicName id="01FAEB768C1102CC40C61D7E33DD2129" authorityName="L., Sp. Pl. 1: 153. 1753. (Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus" order="Solanales" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="C562400A32778393141EF216E6D1555F" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Convolvulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
these specimens may represent plants of hybrid origin.
</paragraph>
